In Compose, you can handle the back button press using the `BackHandler` composable function from the `androidx.compose.ui.platform` package. Here's an example of how you can use it:

```kotlin
import androidx.compose.runtime.Composable
import androidx.compose.ui.platform.LocalLifecycleOwner
import androidx.lifecycle.Lifecycle
import androidx.lifecycle.LifecycleEventObserver

@Composable
fun BackButtonHandler(
    enabled: Boolean = true,
    onBackPressed: () -> Unit
) {
    val lifecycleOwner = LocalLifecycleOwner.current
    DisposableEffect(lifecycleOwner) {
        val observer = LifecycleEventObserver { _, event ->
            if (enabled && event == Lifecycle.Event.ON_RESUME) {
                BackHandler {
                    onBackPressed()
                }
            }
        }

        lifecycleOwner.lifecycle.addObserver(observer)

        onDispose {
            lifecycleOwner.lifecycle.removeObserver(observer)
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `BackButtonHandler` composable function takes two parameters:

- `enabled`: A boolean that determines whether the back button handler should be enabled or not. By default, it's set to `true`.
- `onBackPressed`: A lambda function that will be executed when the back button is pressed.

Inside the `BackButtonHandler` composable, we use the `DisposableEffect` composable to set up and clean up the `LifecycleEventObserver`. The observer listens for the `ON_RESUME` lifecycle event, and when it occurs, it sets up the `BackHandler` composable from the `androidx.compose.ui.platform` package.

The `BackHandler` composable takes a lambda function as a parameter, which is executed when the back button is pressed. In this case, we call the `onBackPressed` lambda function provided to the `BackButtonHandler` composable.

To use the `BackButtonHandler` composable, you can call it within your Composable function, like this:

```kotlin
@Composable
fun MyScreen() {
    BackButtonHandler {
        // Handle back button press here
        // e.g., navigate back, show a dialog, etc.
    }

    // Your screen content goes here
}
```

When the back button is pressed, the `onBackPressed` lambda function will be executed, allowing you to handle the back button press as needed (e.g., navigate back, show a dialog, etc.).

